misconceptions.student_thought_process: The student believes they can scan the array from left to right, stop at the first match using `break`, and then use the loop index after the loop to decide whether a match was found (i == n means not found).
misconceptions.conceptual_gap: No conceptual gap here: in Java, `break` exits the loop immediately, and the loop variable `i` retains its value after the loop. If the loop completes normally, `i` becomes `n`. This matches the intended algorithm for 'first occurrence'.
misconceptions.error_manifestation: None; produces correct index or -1 as required.

evidence.code_snippet:
if(i==n)System.out.println("Found at index: -1");
else System.out.println("Found at index: "+i);
